\section*{Dimensions and Units}

We note that when we take the scalar part of a vector perturbation the
dimension of the quantity changes by one length factor (L) i.e.
\be
\left[V\right] = L \left[{V_i}\right]  \,.
\ee
We also not that when moving to Fourier space quantities will have
three extra length dimension units, i.e.
\be
\left[V (k) \right] = L^3 \left[{V}(x) \right]  \,.
\ee
Finally we list some of the quantities we work with and their dimensions,
where L represents a length dimension, m, a mass dimension, t a time dimension and B a magnetic dimension,
such as Tesla or Gauss. Note that the magnetic units are related to the charge units by,
$T = kg C^{-1} s^{-1}$.
\bea
%\left[B\right] &=& \left[v\right] = \left[V\right] = m \nonumber \\
\left[B_i\right] &=& \left[v_i\right] = \left[{V_i}\right] = 1 \nonumber \\
\left[\phi_1\right] &=& 1 \nonumber \\
\left[u_i\right] &=& m t^{-1} \nonumber \\
\left[\eta\right] &=& t \nonumber \\
\left[\M_i(x,\eta)\right] &=& B \nonumber \\
\left[\E_i(x,\eta)\right] &=& M L t^{-1} \nonumber \\
% \left[\M (x,\eta)\right] &=& Tm \nonumber \\
% \left[\E (x,\eta)\right] &=& T m^2 s^{-1} \nonumber \\
% \left[\M_i(k,\eta)\right] &=& T m^3 \nonumber \\
% \left[\E_i(k,\eta)\right] &=& T m^4 s^{-1} \nonumber \\
% \left[\M (k,\eta)\right] &=& Tm^4 \nonumber \\
% \left[\E (k,\eta)\right] &=& T m^5 s^{-1} \nonumber 
% \eea
% \bea
\left[\mu_0 \J(x,\eta)\right] &=& B \nonumber \\
% \left[\mu_0 \J_i(x,\eta)\right] &=& T m^{-1} \nonumber \\
%\left[\mu_0 c \hat{\rho}\right] &=& T m^{-1} \nonumber \\
%\left[\mu_0\right] &=& kg m C^{-2} \nonumber \\
\left[\rho(x,\eta)\right] &=& \left[\drho(x,\eta) \right] = m L^{-3} \nonumber \\
\left[P(x,\eta)\right] &=& \left[\dP(x,\eta)\right] = m L^{-1} t^{-2} \nonumber 
%\left[\rho(k,\eta)\right] &=& \left[\drho(k,\eta) \right] = kg \nonumber \\
%\left[P(k,\eta)\right] &=& \left[\dP(k,\eta)\right] = kg m^{2} s^{-2} \nonumber 
\eea



